page.title: 01Summary
page.content: This area of natural beauty in the Chilterns is on the hills to the north of the 700 years old town of High Wycombe.Before the late 1950s the villages of Naphill,Downley and Cryer's Hill were small hilltop communities with another residential area in Hughenden Valley.Housing estates,built from the 1960s onwards,have greatly increased the size of these villages, roads have been improved and schools built. A large proportion of the land is agricultural with about a fifth of the total area covered by woodland,largely beech with some mixed deciduous and coniferous areas.There are some small industrial areas,one furniture factory, the headquarters of TRADA and a conference centre. Hughenden Manor,a National Trust property,is a tourist attraction.
